INSERT INTO `troy_courses` (`id`, `courseName`, `courseId`, `subjectId`, `courseStartTime`, `courseEndTime`, `courseAvai`, `courseCapa`, `courseTerm`, `courseStat`, `courseLoca`, `courseDesc`, `courseCred`, `courseLevel`, `courseProfId`) VALUES
(2, 'Fundamentals of Algebra', 1100, 1, 17, 18, 30, 30, 3, 1, 'Troy', 'Topics include integer and rational arithmetic, linear equations, inequalities, integer exponents, polynomials and factoring, rational expression. Prerequisite: Placement or a grade of C or better in MTH 0096. Note: This course is for institutional credit only and will not be used in meeting degree requirements. This course will not substitute for any general studies requirement.', '3.00', 1, 5),
(3, 'Introductory Spanish II', 1142, 3, 8, 9, 30, 30, 3, 1, 'Troy', 'Introduction to the Spanish language and cultures.', '3.00', 1, 3),
(4, 'computer science i', 2250, 1, 9, 10, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'An introduction to the theory and development aspects of a high-level programming language. The course covers programming methodologies, control structures, predefined and user defined functions input/output streams, control structures, logical expressions, enumeration, repetition, multidimensional array and string manipulation, structs, searching, sorting techniques and advanced input/output. Program analysis, design, development and testing are emphasized. Prerequisite MTH 1112', '3.00', 1, 3),
(8, 'computer science ii', 2255, 1, 8, 10, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'A continuation of Computer Science I to include advanced programming techniques including classes and data abstrations, inheritance and composition pointers, virtual functions, overloading, exception handling, and recursion. Students analyze design, develop implement and test complex program. Prerequisite: CS 2250 ', '3.00', 1, 2),
(9, 'Foundations Computer Science', 3310, 1, 12, 13, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'A broad perspective of computer science concepts intended as preparation for more in-depth coverage in higher level courses. Topics include machine and assembly language programming, computer system organization and operation, logic circuits, finite-state diagrams and programming language grammar, Boolean algebra and circuit design con- sideration. Prerequisite: MTH 1112', '3.00', 1, 2),
(10, 'Data Structures', 3323, 1, 8, 10, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'A survey of data structures that includes lists, ordered lists, linked lists, stacks, queues, and trees. Also included are measurement of program performance and how program performance is affecte by alternative data structures. These concepts are presented within an object-oriented framework. Programming labs are included. Prerequisite: CS 2260, MTH 1125, 2215.', '3.00', 1, 3),
(11, ' Software Engineering I', 3332, 1, 11, 13, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'opics are presented that focus on the design and development techniques for large high quality soft ware systems. They include project management issues, analysis and design methods, and ap- proaches to testing. Prerequisite: CS 3323 or 3330 ', '3.00', 1, 1),
(12, 'Analysis of Algorithms', 3329, 1, 12, 13, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'Alternative techniques to solve computer science problems are presented. Problems include sorting, searching, and graph traversal, lists, ordered lists, linked lists, stacks, queues, and trees. These concepts are presented within an object- oriented framework. Prerequisite: CS 3323 ', '3.00', 1, 4),
(13, 'Concepts of Obj Program I', 3360, 1, 13, 15, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'Provides student the opportunity to gain experience and training in an additional high level language. The course focuses on advanced topics including classes, objects, interfaces, appplications, encapsulation, exceptions, multithreading, graphics, exception handling, files and streaming. Prerequisite: CS 2255', '3.00', 1, 2),
(14, 'Nature of Programming Lang', 3370, 1, 10, 11, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'Basic principles and concepts of programming lan- guages including what a programming language is, various paradigms that a language can follow, and how its syntactical and sematic structures can be specified. The traditional object-oriented para- digm will be presented as well as non-traditional paradigms based on symbolic logic (logic program- ming) and on functions in lambda calculus (func- tional programming). Prerequisites: CS 3323 or 3330 ', '3.00', 1, 2),
(15, 'Formal Lang  Thry of Comp', 3372, 1, 13, 14, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'ormal language theory, including the Chomsky hierarchy is presented. Emphasis is placed on reg- ular and context free grammars, finite state automata, and translators. Prerequisite: CS 3323 or 3330 ', '3.00', 1, 2),
(16, 'Introduction to Database Syst', 4420, 1, 11, 12, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'The fundamental concepts and structures necessary for the design and implementation of a database management system. Students design, loads and query a database using tools such as E-R diagrams and SQL. Also includes data normalization and file and index orgranization. Prerequisite: CS 3323 or CS 3330', '3.00', 1, 4),
(17, 'Data Communication and Networkin', 4445, 1, 8, 9, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'An overview of local-area and wide-area systems. Issues discussed include standards, topologies, management, communication protocol and security. Prerequisite: CS 3323 or 3330. Students majoring in Applied Computer Science or the Computer Science Program may not apply this course to the Cyber Security minor or certification. ', '3.00', 1, 1),
(18, 'Operating Systems', 4448, 1, 13, 14, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'An overview of operating system functions and com- ponents. Issues include process definition, sche- duling, and memory management. Various modern operating systems are compared. Prerequisites: CS 3323 or 3330', '3.00', 1, 3),
(27, 'world regional geography', 2210, 1, 14, 17, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'patterson hall 203 ', '3.00', 1, 28),
(28, 'visual art', 1133, 36, 10, 12, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'patterson hall 303 \r\nThe visual arts and their relationship to human needs and aspirations. NOTE: Credit for this course may not be applied toward any program in art.', '3.00', 1, 20),
(37, 'Comp and Modern English I', 1101, 40, 9, 10, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'SMTH Smith Hall, Room 159\r\nIntensive instruction in the writing process. Focuses on organization of ideas in well-developed expository and argumentative essays (usually 6 to 8 essays), with stress on grammar, punctuation, and vocabulary development. A grade of C or better is required for credit. Must be completed within the first 30 hours of enrollment. Prerequisite: Placement Test', '3.00', 1, 37),
(38, 'Comp and Modern English II', 1102, 40, 11, 12, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'SMTH Smith Hall, Room 155\r\nText-based analyses and application of principles and tools of research in writing short research papers. A grade of C or better is required for credit. Must be taken within the first 30 hours of enrollment. Prereguisite: ENG 1101 or equivalent.', '3.00', 1, 37),
(39, 'World Literature After ', 2206, 40, 13, 14, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'SMTH Smith Hall, Room 164\r\nIntroduction to attitudes, philosophies, and reflections of life in world literary masterpieces from the Enlightenment to the present. Required demonstration of acceptable writing skills. Pre- requisite: ENG 1102 or equivalent', '3.00', 1, 30),
(41, 'Biochemistry', 3352, 9, 14, 15, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', ' MSCX Math/Science, Room 318\r\nThis course describes the molecular basis of life and discusses the structure, function and metabolism of proteins, carbohydrated, lipids and nucleic acids. Prerequisites: CHM 3343/L343. ', '3.00', 1, 17),
(42, 'General Physics', 2252, 21, 8, 10, 35, 35, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 118\r\n\r\nAn introduction to the laws of mechanics and thermodynamics. Prerequisite: MTH 1114 or 1115', '3.00', 1, 1),
(43, 'Calculus and Its Applications', 2201, 1, 11, 12, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 230\r\nAn introduction to the basic ideas and techniques of differential and integral calculus, especially as they relate to problems involving maximum and minimum values of functions and marginial analysis Prerequisite: A grade of C of better in MTH 1112 or 1115 or advanced placement. ', '3.00', 1, 14),
(45, 'foundations speech', 2241, 37, 9, 10, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'modern language for communication skills development as interview.', '3.00', 1, 32),
(46, 'Calculus', 2225, 2, 9, 10, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'vector calculus high level math subject.', '4.00', 1, 14),
(48, 'linear algebra', 3331, 2, 8, 9, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 226\r\nMatrices, systems of equations, determinants, eigenvalues and eigenvectors. Prerequisites; MTH 1126.', '3.00', 1, 14),
(49, 'intro to advanced mathematics', 3318, 2, 13, 14, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 228\r\nTopics include set theory, equivalence relations and partitions, logic, number systems, functions, and proof writing techniques. Prerequisites: MTH 1126', '3.00', 1, 6),
(50, 'stat methods and computations', 3350, 2, 14, 16, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 230\r\nThis course is designed to provide students with a foundation in statistical methods, including data exploring and strategies in sample surveys, estimation and testing hypotheses of means and variances, analysis of variance, regression analysis, contingency tables. These concepts are taught with heavy emphasis on statistical computing software and real world datasets. Students will use basic skills of SAS, a statistical software package that is widely used in business, industry, government, and research.', '3.00', 1, 11),
(51, 'Complex Analysis', 4426, 2, 11, 12, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 224\r\nComplex number, elementary functions and their mappings, complex limits, and power series, anal- ytic functions, integrals, countour integral, and Cauchy integral formula. Prerequisite: MTH 2227 and 3318', '3.00', 1, 14),
(52, 'real analysis', 5524, 2, 17, 20, 5, 5, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 226\r\nA study of the real number system, completeness, limits, continuity, sequences, differentiation and the Riemann integral', '3.00', 2, 14),
(53, 'computer architecture', 5545, 1, 17, 20, 20, 20, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 218\r\nFunctional descriptions of the major components of digital computer architectures are explored, such as arithmetic and control units, memory hierarchies, channels and characterizations and interactions of individual major components of small an large computers. Also included are minicomputer architectures, specialized computer architectures, and distributed data processing architectures.', '3.00', 2, 4),
(56, 'Operating Systems principles', 5550, 1, 11, 12, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 218\r\nThis course discusses what operating systems are, what they do, how they are designed and organized. Topics discussed include: Process Management (scheduling intercommunication, synchronization, and deadlock handling), storage (management and virtual memory management), I/O systems(hardware, interfaces, request-handeling, performance issues) Applications of these concepts in modern operating systems such as Windows and Unix are presented', '3.00', 2, 2),
(57, 'advanced software engineering', 6680, 1, 11, 13, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 218\r\nThis course covers advanced theoretical concepts in software engineering. Topics include software development models, requirement analysis, project planning and management, software architecture and design, implementation, and testing and validation. ', '3.00', 2, 1),
(58, 'survay of law enforcement', 2221, 11, 13, 14, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 328\r\nA survey of policing, covering developmental history, the system of law enforcement, organi-zations in the U.S., personnel administration, police roles and behavior, operations, major issues such as discretion, civil liability, risk and excessive force. ', '3.00', 1, 35),
(59, 'private and public security adm', 3335, 11, 15, 17, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 328\r\nAn introduction to the administration of private security, the analog to the police in the public sector. Issues in private security concerning ethics, law and policy, as well as administration, are considered', '3.00', 1, 9),
(60, 'intro to social science inq', 3375, 11, 10, 11, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'BGRV Bibb Graves, Room 241\r\nPrinciples of pure and applied research for the social sciences. Special emphasis is given to the types of research methods employed by social sci- entists including survey techniques, field research, quasi-experimental designs and analytical procedures currently used in the social sciences.', '3.00', 1, 36),
(61, 'criminology', 3345, 11, 15, 18, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 318\r\nAn examination of crime, overall and by category, and an examination of theories of crime causation, their research support and their impact on social policy, categories of crime, etc. The crim-inological theories covered will be classical, biological, sociological, psychological, economic and multidisciplinary. ', '3.00', 1, 47),
(62, 'Digital Forensics', 3380, 11, 11, 12, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', ' BGRV Bibb Graves, Room 239\r\nBasic course designed to introduce the students to identifying and collecting digital data, analyzing the data through the use of forensics tools (hands on) and presenting it in a written report. ', '3.00', 1, 29),
(63, 'criminal invest ecidence', 4442, 11, 9, 10, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 116\r\nA detailed examination of what is necessary to solve criminal cases and prove guilty beyond a reasonable doubt. Emphasis on leadership and management actions taken to enhance investigative efforts in any law enforcement operation. ', '3.00', 1, 39),
(64, 'cyber crime', 4472, 11, 10, 11, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'BGRV Bibb Graves, Room 239\r\nThis course will introduce the topics of computer crime and computer forensics. Students will be required to learn different aspects of computer crime and ways in which to uncover, protect and exploit digital evidence. Students will be exposed to different types of tools, both software and hardware and an exploration of the legal issues affected by online and computer related criminal conduct. The course will examine the evolution of criminal law relative to the development of new technology.', '3.00', 1, 18),
(65, 'mamagerial cost accounting', 3395, 25, 13, 14, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'BGRV Bibb Graves, Room 147\r\nAn analysis of issues dealing with cost accounting and cost management in the global economy from the viewpoint of management, including calculating product costs and period expenses, cost systems for accululating and managing costs, analyzing cost behavior for tactical decisions, introduc- tion to activity-based costing, ethical principles for management accountants measuring the costs of quality and preparing the master budget. Accounting majors must complete this courses with a grade of C or better. ', '3.00', 1, 34),
(66, 'anthropology', 2200, 7, 10, 11, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MSCX Math/Science, Room 114\r\nAn examination of human, physical and cultural development using evidence from archaeology, paleontology, genetics, ecology, cultural anthropology and linguistics with emphasis on the historical, structural and symbolic aspects of human culture. This course is a prerequisite for all 3300 and 4400 level courses in anthropology', '3.00', 1, 47),
(67, 'Foundations of form and space', 1145, 36, 10, 11, 25, 25, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MALN Malone Hall, Room 201\r\nIntroduction to the principles, elements and concepts of two-dimensional space', '3.00', 1, 47),
(68, 'senior thesis', 4499, 36, 10, 12, 30, 30, 1, 1, 'Troy', 'MALN Malone Hall, Room 118\r\nRequirement for all graduating art or design majors in a comprehensive program of study. Production of a body of work related to their area of concentration and the production of a written manifesto and statement. All students in the BFA and <> programs must take this course in one on their last two semesters prior to graduation. This class is not offered in the Summer Semester', '3.00', 1, 9);
